{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"classless-splintery-noctule","description":"## Why\n\nGerrit-side signing (review-bot signing 245e, reconciler inline-sign 9e76, opcert-service)\nlanded **in code**, but the post-deploy validation canary 1787 was **force-closed \"pending\npost-deploy run\"** — it was never confirmed that the deployed rebar-gerrit VM services\nactually sign their ticket writes. Flipping enforcement would turn Gerrit-originated ticket\nwrites red.\n\n## What\n\nConfirm the deployed VM services sign, finishing what canary 1787 deferred:\n\n- On the deployed rebar-gerrit VM, verify each ticket-writing service (review-bot,\n  reconciler, opcert-service) has a materialized `0600` signing key and a `git user.email`\n  matching its identity.\n- Re-run the canary end-to-end and confirm a real Gerrit-originated ticket write is signed.\n\n## Scope\n\nThe deployed Gerrit VM services that write tickets: verification plus any missing key\nprovisioning. No enforcement flip here.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Each Gerrit-side service that writes tickets has a materialized `0600` signing key and\n      a git email matching its identity.\n- [ ] A real Gerrit-originated ticket write produces a **signed** event; `rebar\n      verify-identity` reports it `verified`.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] the canary is re-run on the deployed VM and its signed event id /\n      log is recorded on this ticket.","id":"1a51-b170-5168-46d2","parent_id":"dc09-6565-cf85-4aea","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Confirm Gerrit-side services sign ticket writes on the deployed VM (finish canary 1787)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784226822054405001,"uuid":"429251cb-f18a-438b-899a-38f2da9d4b26"}